As I understand it your question is that you want to take a list of filenames that contains either zero, one or more than one items and you want to take different actions in each case. Among the actions you want to take is to read the names of the files in a specific directory and compare them to a filename from your original list.

The first problem I see with your code is that you&#39;re specifying your list as a character array:

    compare=[&#39;a&#39;;&#39;s&#39;];

This may give you problems when it comes to comparing, as each filename will get padded with spaces to make it the same length as the longest one. Use a **cell array of strings** instead. To check how many items are in this array, use `length`.

Next you want to get the contents of a directory:

    compare = dir;
    compare = compare(~[compare.isdir]);

That&#39;s OK and gives you a struct array with details of all the files but not the directories. But this

    compare = compare(~[FileNrOne]);

is meaningless because as far as I can see `FileNrOne` is supposed to be a character array, and `~[&#39;some character array&#39;]` just returns a logical array the length of the character array with all elements false. If you have a struct array from `dir` - let&#39;s call it `dirResult` - and you want to remove the element whose name is `removeMe`, do:

    dirResult = dirResult(~strcmpi(removeMe, {dir.name}));

Use `strcmpi` if your file system is case-insensitive (Windows, Mac usually) or `strcmp` if it&#39;s case-sensitive (Linux).

If this answer doesn&#39;t enable you to fix your problem, please update your question with more detail of exactly what is going wrong, or ask a new and more specific question.

