As Olivier Rogier already said: you can&#39;t. 

What you can do is something like:

    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        Dictionary&lt;string, object&gt; toLog = new Dictionary&lt;string, object&gt;();
        toLog.Add(&quot;today&quot;, DateTime.Today);
        toLog.Add(&quot;tomorrow&quot;, DateTime.Today.AddDays(1));
        Log(toLog );

        Console.ReadKey();
    }

    public static void Log(Dictionary&lt;string, object&gt; toLog)
    {
        foreach (var kvp in toLog)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(kvp.Key);   
            Console.WriteLine(kvp.Value);
        }
    }

To answer your question, let&#39;s first understand what your code is doing:

* `new { today }` is shorthand for `new { today = today }`.
* The `new { }` syntax will create an anonymous type to hold this data. Basically you are creating two classes here, one with a &quot;today&quot; property, and one with a &quot;tomorrow&quot; property.

See [anonymous types documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/classes-and-structs/anonymous-types) for more information.

**I would advise against doing it this way, and instead use a dictionary, a list of KeyValuePair&lt;string, Datetime&gt;, or some other data structure that holds the data how you want it.**

Anyway, since these are single-property classes, you could retrieve the property something like this:

    var properties = field.GetType().GetProperties();
    if (properties.Count() == 1)
    {
        var property = properties.Single();
        Console.WriteLine(property.Name);
        Console.WriteLine(property.GetValue(field));
    }
	
I strongly recommend something like Thomas Vo&#223;&#39;s [answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58324498/3181933) instead of doing this.

If you were you were to use a dictionary, you could use `nameof` with your variables:

    var today = DateTime.Today;
    var tomorrow = DateTime.Today.AddDays(1);
    var myValues = new Dictionary&lt;string, object&gt;();
    myValues[nameof(today)] = today;
    myValues[nameof(tomorrow)] = tomorrow;
    myValues[&quot;test&quot;] = &quot;hello&quot;;

    foreach (var field in myValues)
    {
        Console.WriteLine(field.Key);
        Console.WriteLine(field.Value);
    }

[Try it online](https://dotnetfiddle.net/lmlfYY)

You didn&#39;t mention which version of `C#` or `.NET` you&#39;re using, but if `KeyValuePair&lt;string, object&gt;` and `Tuple&lt;string, object&gt;` are too verbose for you then you could try `ValueTuple` as long as you&#39;re on `C#` 7.

```lang-csharp
public void Main()
{
   Log((&quot;today&quot;, DateTime.Today), (&quot;tomorrow&quot;, DateTime.Today.AddDays(1)));
}

public void Log(params (string Name, object Value)[] values)
{
   foreach (var value in values)
   {
      Console.WriteLine($&quot;{value.Name} =&gt; {value.Value}&quot;);
   }
}
```

